QD1_Comment: Arizona underwent “Redistricting” prior to the 2012 General Election and part of the redistricting efforts for Maricopa County was to redraw and consolidate precincts.  Prior to 2012, Maricopa County had 1,124 precincts (since 2006).  With the increase in the number of voters in Maricopa County on the Permanent Early Voting List (1,162,067), we were able to merge several precincts to reach a new precinct total for 2012 of 724 precincts.
QD2_Comment: D2a is a total number of physical polling places (677) IN ADDITION to the 15 early voting centers (3 offices and 12 off-site locations) and the 5 drop off “ballot box” sites for a total of 697.  “Election Day” voting (D2b) is only offered at polling place locations.  Each of the 724 precincts is technically assigned a polling place.  However, in certain areas some precinct polling places were co-located within the same facility and that is why the "physical" polling place location total is less than the number of precincts existing.  A co-located polling place consists of two different and separate boards specifically assigned to a given precinct and a specific set of voters within that precinct.  Additionally, we had 7 All-Mail Precincts where the total number of registered voters within those precincts was less than 25 registered voters.  These All-Mail precincts were still co-located and assigned to a physical polling place in case a voter opted to vote in-person versus by mail.
QD3_Comment: As a note, we also hired 119 citizen board Troubleshooters that do not serve as polling place board workers but are assigned several specific polling place locations to assist the board workers at these locations with any issues that come up on Election Day. This quantity of additional workers (119) is NOT reflected in the above grand total.
QD4_Comment: Maricopa County implemented "Student" poll workers program back in 2008.  Since its inception, we have seen a steady increase in participation amongst students.  For this 2012 General election, of the 4,820 workers, we had over 167 of these board workers that were "Student" poll workers.
QD5_Comment: The recruitment process was neither difficult nor easy.  By this we mean with the 724 precincts (677 physical polling locations) we have here in Maricopa County, we found many polling places where we had a surplus of workers due to the more populace location which then made it easy to locate sufficient number of board workers.  However, in some rural areas, it was somewhat difficult to recruit poll workers.  We do ask poll workers to work outside of their precinct but many of the rural areas were just too far for some out-of-precinct workers to accept.

QD5_Comment: Rather difficult to find Democrats and younger workers.
The best window seems to be 61- to 70-year-old who recently retired.  Many are used to being active and are looking fro something to do.
It has been more difficult with a dual ballot to find bi-lingual poll workers who can translate correctly and are registered and have voted before.
Somewhat difficult to find younger workers since most are in the work force.  Older workers do not want to give up being an election worker.

Able to fill positions because they recruit board workers at every election.  Poll workers are recruited or when they retire from service, thy are asked to pass on poll worker applications to others they may know.  It also appears voters in the county have a positive sense of civic responsibilith and are willing to volunteer as a board worker.
Many poll workers want to return, but the difficulty is balancing each receiving board between the required political parties.  Having on-call workers is a big help.
County has difficulty finding non-Republican poll workers due to county demographics.
Younger workers are not easy to find; many would have to take a vacation day or not be paid from their jobs despite state statutes say time must be allowed if they wish.
Political Party Balance

QD3_Comment: In preparation for the 2012 election cycle, the Albany County election staff designed various efforts to recruit new election judges during new voter registrations at the courthouse and through educational testimony during annual off site VR drives.  A mailing was created to generate commitment to participate and when making election judges assignments for the Primary and the General election, the County Clerk and her election staff were thoughtful with regard to pairing seasoned judges with new recruits to facilitate continuity in experiential training.
QD5_Comment: The County Clerk continues to foster cooperative participation and she and her staff provide party chairs, the municipal clerk and other interested associations, opportunity to participate in the election judge recruitment process.  This election cycle, certain parties distributed a call for service via email, while others used a more conservative approach. The County Clerk and her election staff extended multiple invitations to high school aged students to serve in 2012. The county employed three student judges; one during the Primary and two during the General election.
